Data Visualization With Pandas, Matplotlib, & Seaborn¶

The major chart types used in graphing data with Python.

  • Matplotlib: The major library that others are built off of
  • Pandas: Has built in matplotlib functions that allow you to graph based off of a dataframe
  • Seaborn: User-friendly version of matplotlib, has a number of custom chart types that are very handy.

A really important detail is getting the correct dataframe for each graph!

In [1]:
# load in the dataset
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
df = pd.read_csv('../data/titanic.csv')

Seaborn¶

  • A much easier way to do more elaborate plotting
  • Often the best choice for doing exploratory data analysis
  • Built off of Matplotlib
  • Has the following benefits:
    • Built in methods for using column values to adjust the following visual parameters:
    • Default styling palettes that are tasteful
    • Specialty charts that extend basic matplotlib:
    • heatmap
    • jointplot
    • pairplot
    • regression plots
In [32]:
# import seaborn here
import seaborn as sns

Primary Seaborn Chart Types:¶

  • catplot
  • relplot
  • lmplot/regplot
  • distplot/jointplot
  • pairplot

Categorical Data¶

Uses the catplot to accomplish this, with 9 different variants to add visual diversity.

In [33]:
# basic syntax for Seaborn - must specify x and y variables, as well as data source
sns.catplot(x='Pclass', y='Age', data=df)
Out[33]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1e5f9230668>
In [34]:
# if you want to switch chart type, just use the 'kind' argument
sns.catplot(x='Pclass', y='Age', kind='swarm', data=df)
Out[34]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1e5f94f9be0>

Other Useful Arguments in Seaborn:¶

  • hue
  • col/row
In [35]:
# let's take a look at the same graph, but using hue to distinguish male from female
sns.catplot(x='Pclass', y='Age', kind='swarm', hue='Sex', data=df)
Out[35]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1e5f95745c0>
In [36]:
# you can get a similar effect, but using each value as a separate column
sns.catplot(x='Pclass', y='Fare', kind='swarm', col='Sex', data=df)
Out[36]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1e5f95029b0>
In [37]:
# or as a row
sns.catplot(x='Pclass', y='Fare', kind='swarm', row='Sex', data=df)
Out[37]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1e5f965f0f0>

Hue and Col/Row do NOT work on distplots.¶

  • However, you can use subplots, and the ax argument to create overlays
  • Overlays using the ax argument will not work on jointplots
In [42]:
Image(filename='plot6.jpg')
Out[42]:
In [ ]:
# this code would give you the previous plot
ax = sns.distplot(df[df.Sex == 'female']['Age'], label='Females')
sns.distplot(df[df.Sex == 'male']['Age'], label='Males', ax=ax)
plt.legend(loc='best')
